Over the last 10 days, the price dropped below $400 once, but always closed above. Over the last month, it closed below 400 once, but generally remained above. Looking further back, however, we can see how volatile the stock really is. Investors appear to move rapidly in and out of Tesla - on 31 August the stock closed at about $500 and barely over a week later it had dropped to $330 (I believe on news that it was not added to the Dow as it was expected to be).

Sell off from the gap up today gets rid of sellers at the previous peaks around $460. Buyers have to show they are willing to step in above $430 for the third basket to have a chance. I will watch dutifully today and tomorrow's open before making a final prediction.

Tesla currently priced at c.440 so that will be my base case. Crowd forecast suggest below 400 is very unlikely but it was below 400 at the end of October and given its volatility (I think in part because it is a news worthy stock) I think there is more of a chance of it dropping below 400. On the other end, rising to above 520 would mean an 18% rise in less than two weeks and hitting an all time high. While not impossible this seems highly unlikely. While I have 440 as the current base, contending with news of a likely end of year bull run on the stock market in general pushes the likelihood into the 440-480 range. Tesla loses $ on every car produced. Tesla records profits based on zero emission vehicle (ZEV) credits. Tesla sells $5000 credit per vehicle for ~$2000 to other auto manufacturers. Tesla gets +$6500 per vehicle based on range multipliers. As others roll out electrics those payments will reduce. I suspect more difficult road head for Tesla. All this info per Forbes. Minimal impact in this timeline, however.

Tesla is on schedule to deliver 500,000 vehicles this year due to improved manufacturing in China. Forbes experts a 13.7% climb over the next year ($500). To reach that goal in two months seems unreasonable. I can't see the prices fall dramatically without something catastrophic occurring.

I looked at percentage changes after 35 days from mid-April to now (post COVID novelty noise), which suggests it's quite likely to be over $520. Then I combined those numbers with a more arithmetic analysis from a series of trend lines, which were more bearish. Lastly, I regressed to the mean a bit.

Tesla stock has been rapidly rising over the past year and is expected to continue to climb. Based on historical trends, the probability of rising is 55% through the end of the year. At 454 now, the stock is expected to close out in Dec around 450. Tesla continues to innovate in solar, cars and space ensuring accessibility to more people of alternative energy solutions.
